summary.seg: Cambridge University Library, MS Ee.5.22 is a legal manuscript written in England in the later half of the 15th century, probably c. 1485. The vast majority of the texts in this manuscript are in legal French and are copies of a special type of legal text known as 'Readings'. 'Readings' were one of the primary methods by which student and junior lawyers at the Inns of Court in London were instructed in English legal theory and practice before the availability of affordable printed legal textbooks made the need for 'Readings' obsolete. Each year, senior members at each of the Inns of Court would be elected as 'Readers' to give regular 'Readings' for half a year or a year on particular legal topics and statutes. At the 'Readings', statutes and other legal texts would be read aloud by the Reader who would also lecture the audience on the significance of the text. Legal students and junior lawyers would then be asked to debate matters of legal theory arising from the Reading or would take part in mock debates based on what they had just heard. Readings were an important part of legal education in England before the widespread availability of printed legal textbooks, and copies of Readings made by students in the audience (or subsequent recopies of those texts) are present in a number of surviving manuscripts. The original owner and copier of CUL MS Ee.5.22 is unknown, but Baker and Ringrose determined that it is likely that he was a member of Gray's Inn as a note on f. 184v, 'mez secundum Borell', establishes a connection with Gray's Inn as at least one, if not two members of the Inn in the late-15th century had the surname Borell. Readers are encouraged to consult the Baker and Ringrose Catalogue of English Legal Manuscripts for further information.

References:
J. H. Baker, and J. S. Ringrose, A Catalogue of English Legal Manuscripts in Cambridge University Library, with Codicological Descriptions of the Early Manuscripts (Woodbridge: Boydell Press, 1996)

note.p: Note of a grant by an Elizabeth ?Shrop (Scrope) to a Richard Nevyle of the office of steward of a manor. The grant mentions a place called 'Sonyngton' and the text says that that place is also known as 'Sundon' - this probably refers to the manor of Sundon in Bedfordshire, which is spelled as 'Sonedone' and 'Sonyngdon' in various medieval sources. The manor of Sundon came under the control of the Scrope family after the death of its owner Robert Tiptot in 1372. When Tiptot died in 1372, he left behind three young female children, whose wardship was given to Richard le Scrope, 1st Baron Scrope of Bolton (b. c. 1327, d. 30 May 1403). In 1385 Richard le Scrope's son, Roger le Scrope, married Tiptot's daughter and heir Margaret and so the manor of Sundon passed into the Scrope family through that marriage. Although the precise compilation date of CUL MS Ee.5.22 is unknown, the volume probably dates from the final quarter of the 15th century (c. 1485) and there were two Elizabeth Scropes alive in 1485 who may have been parties to the grant. John Scrope, 5th Baron Scrope of Bolton married Elizabeth St John at an unknown date before 10 December 1471; it is not known when the marriage ended, but Elizabeth must have died before 3 July 1494 (and possibly before 1490) as another marriage is recorded for John Scrope after that date. John Scrope, 5th Baron Scrope of Bolton and Elizabeth St John had a son, Henry Scrope, 6th Baron Scrope of Bolton (b. c. 1468, d. c. 1506) who married Elizabeth Percy, a daughter of Henry Percy, 3rd Earl of Northumberland c. 1480. The 'Richard Nevyle' mentioned in the grant probably cannot be identified with any precision as there were several members of the family with that name alive in the late 15th century. The Scropes had a close relationship with the Neville family in the 15th century and had acted as guardians for each others children and had formed marriage alliances between various branches of their families and so this grant doubtless refers to a transaction between these two intertwined families.
Much of the text is unclear due to damage to the leaf.

msItem.title: Merton
msItem.incipit: 52r De uiduis que post mortem uiuorum suorum etc. Sur cest estatut fuit reherce que al comen ley quaunt home espous un feme pur lobseruance que la feme ad fait al baron la ley uoet que par luy ele auera son uiand et benefice
msItem.note: According to Baker and Ringrose this Item contains: 'Readings on the Statute of Merton, cc. 1-10. The named disputants are: 54r [Alexander' Anne (d. 1438), [Robert] Kyrkelad, [Gilbert Halt[oft] (d. 1458); 60v [Thomas] Cokayne (d. 1440), [John] Hody (d. 1441); 66r Hodye; 68v [John] Mark[ham] (d. 1479), Halt[oft]. Parts of it are also in Cambridge, University Library, MS Hh.3.6, ff. 23r-28v; Cambridge, University Library, MS Ee.5.19, ff. 156r-170v; and Cambridge, University Library, MS Ii.5.43, ff. 42v-51v . It seems to be an early Gray's Inn reading, probably Haltoft's own, since Haltoft is reported twice as answering objections made against the reader. Thorne (Readings, I. xx, lviii) dated it just before 1430. He surmised that two readings here had been merged into one text. The part involving Cokayne and Hody may derive from a Middle Temple reading c. 1430.: cf. Hh.3.6, ff. 23r-28v. Substantial extracts from the whole are printed in Readings, I. xc-cxiii. On 73v is a note: 'ajugge en assise devant Cheyne et Martyn en Cornewaill' (i.e. 1417/24).'

msItem.title: Ihc. Westm. primer capitulo primo
msItem.incipit: 115r Pur ceo que nostre seignior le Roy etc. Le myschif deuaunt le fesaunce de cest estatute fuit que quaunt seigniorz uicontes et auterz homez uoillent uener a abbies priorys et auterz measonz de religion et la auer manger et boyer et surcharge le meason
msItem.note: According to Baker and Ringrose this is: '[a]n anonymous reading on Westminster I, cc. 1-48 (but with several chapters omitted). Some matter from the 1450s is cited in the text: 121r Jack Cade; 145v a statute of 39 Hen VI; 150r a case of 35 Hen. VI; and on 119r is a case 'jades ... deuaunt M. Litilton'. On 143r: 'fuit adjuge et tenuz cest an darreyne passe que lou un auoit deliuer a un cariar certein bienz ...', which seems to be a reference to the Carrier's Case (1473), Seldon Soc. 64: 30. A date in the time of Edw. IV would be consistent woth two references to 'temps le Roy H. vi'. Thorne, however (Readings lvii), thought the Edw. IV material had been added to an earlier reading. This is not wholly clear, especially since there are blanks in the text for additions and yet the Edw. IV text is incorporated in the text as written and not added. See Selden Soc. 94, chap. X and p. 348 (siglum H).'
Folios 116v, 131r, 147, 151r, 153r, 155v, 158v-159v, 165v blank except for running titles. 171v-172r blank.

msItem.title: Reading on the statute of Gloucester
msItem.incipit: 175r Come auant cez hourez damagez ne furent agardez etc. Al comen ley le mischief fuit que si le disseisor ne fuit sufficient de render damagez taxez per lassise al pleyntif il fuit saunz remedie
msItem.note: According to Baker and Ringrose this is: '[a]n anonymous reading on the statute of Gloucester, cc. 1-15. A name on 184v ('mez secundum Borell ...') establishes the provenance as Gray's Inn. 'Mr Borell of gras In' was a mid-xv cent. benefactor to St Andrew's Holborn: London, Guildhall, MS 4249, f. 221v. 'John Borell of greys yn gentleman' is mentioned in a will of 1469: PROB 11/6, f. 38v (P.C.C. 6 Wattys). An Andrew Borel, formerly of Furnival's Inn, was buried in St Michael's, Crooked Lane, London, as of Gray's Inn (d. 1487); J. Stow, Survey of London (C. L. Kingsford ed.) 2:222. See Selden Soc. 94, chap. X and p. 349 (siglum K).'

On 269v 'loppinion de Newenton est ...' (as in Hh.2.8, f. 51r). On 291r the names of Warbulton and Newton occur. If this is Richard Newton Richard Newton (d. 1448) (d. 1448), created serjeant in 1425, this may be a pre-1448 Middle Temple reading. William Warbelton William Warbelton (d. 1469) (d. 1469) was M.P. Hants. from 1425, J.P. Hants. from 1431. This interchange also occurs in 6 other manuscripts containing related texts: Cambridge, University Library, MS Hh.2.8, f. 58v, London, British Library, MS Harley 7536, f. 33v, London, British Library, MS Lansdowne 465, f. 61r, Oxford, Bodleian Library, MS Rawlinson C.294, f. 154r, Oxford, University College, MS 163, f. 227r and Washington D.C, Library of Congress, (Law Division) MS 29, f. 57v. On 245r, a passage temp. Edw. IV referring to 'loppinion de Litilton justice ... a quel opinion Uauasour se agrea' may be an interpolation from an Inner Temple reading in the 1470s: cf. the Catesby interpolations in [Item 7 18r-51r], above. See Thorne, Readings, I.lxvi-lxvii. See Selden Soc. 94, chap. X and p. 349 (siglum O).

msItem.title: Medical recipe
msItem.rubric: 378v A goode medecyn for the moder

note.p:
Folio 378v - full transcription:
A goode medecyn for the moder
Take ix croppis of modirworte , ix of styche worte , ix cro of persele rote and all iij cropis of erbe john al fertherfoy , iij croppis of grounde swely , ix cro of archangel al dul reede nettill , iij croppis of rede fenell an handfull of Betayn a quantite of holy leves þat hath noo prykkes , a quantite of ... tyme rose mary and sauge ryall , take all these and stampe þem to gedire and wrynge owte the juse , but seth your licour ferst and ... it clene be it ale oþer water then putto þe juse of your seide herbis and seth all to gedire , then grynde your spicu and putt therin , a peny worth of notmyggis , a peny worth of longe peper clown maces and greynde , and ob worth in saffron, and putt there in a quantite of hony or els of sugur , then putt it in a glas and stoppe it close , and drynke thereof to beddewarde and herly fastynge
probatus est

supportDesc.support:
Paper, folded in folio, with mutliple watermarks. Watermark: Folios 2r-17v, 97r-114v and 359r-278v(Quires 1, 6, 19): a letter 'P'. Baker and Ringrose draw attention to a similar mark printed in G. Piccard, Wasserzeichen Buchstabe P, (Stuttgart, 1997) 2: Abt. III, 479.
Folios 18r-76v and 338r-358v(Quires 2-4, 18 and also once in Quire 9): a letter 'Y' or 'Þ' surmounted by a cross. Baker and Ringrose note that this mark is close to Briquet no. 9196.
Folios 77r-96v (Quire 5): letter 'P' and according to Baker and Ringrose a 'heraldic device of a lozenge paly of five surmounted by a crown'.
Folios 115r-154v and 175r-316v(Quires 7-8, 10-16): several versions of a bull's head with a star on an antenna between the horns.
Folios 156r-[174a] verso (Quire 9): IHS in a circle.
Folios 317r-337v (Quire 17): several motifs including a bull's head with a star on an antenna between the horns, a bull's head without a star on an antenna between the horns, and IHS in a circle.

foliation.p: 17th century foliation sequence with 20th and 21st century additions and corrections.

note.p: Until the 20th century, the only foliation sequence present in the volume appears to have been the sequence added in ink in the 17th century. The volume sustained significant rodent damage after the addition of the 17th century foliation sequence, and so replacement designations were added in the 20th century in pencil in Hindu-Arabic numerals in the lower outer corner of each recto beginning at f. 315 to redesignate the leaves that had lost their 17th century ink designations due to damage to the leaves.

In 2024, CUL MS Ee.5.22 was catalogued as part of the Curious Cures Project and the foliation sequence in the volume was expanded and emended to ensure that each leaf had a distinguishing designation. The paper endleaves added at each end of the volume during the 18th century rebinding were assigned the designations ff. i and ii respectively. The errors in the 17th century foliation sequence were corrected as follows:
The first of the duplicated folio 52s was struck through in the manuscript at an unknown date; this leaf has been redesignated as f. [51a], and the second folio 52 retains the designation f. 52.
The first of the duplicated folio 133s retains the designation f. 133 and the second has been redesignated as f. [133a].
The first of the duplicated folio 172s retains the designation f. 172 and the second has been redesignated as f. [172a].
The gaps in the foliation sequence due to omitted designations for folios 155, 202, and 233 have been retained - these designations do not exist in the current foliation sequence.
The unfoliated leaf after f. 157 has been assigned the desigation f. [157a].
The unfoliated leaf after f. 174 has been assigned the desigation f. [174a].
Folio designations that have been assigned or corrected during the production of this manuscript record are enclosed in [square brackets] throughout this record.

signatures.p: 15th century leaf signatures in ink in Roman numerals in the lower outer corner of the rectos in the first half of each quire; many of these designations have been lost to trimming and damage.
Quires are numbered in pencil in Hindu-Arabic numerals in the lower outer corner of the first recto of each quire; the designation for Quire 18 has been omitted by the collator.

condition.p: Condition assessment, May 2023. CUL MS Ee.5.22 is in fragile condition: both boards detached at the hinges, half leather covers peeling and flaking, significant damage to the edges of the leaves throughout the bookblock caused by rodents and exposure to damp. A lot of the text in the volume is difficult to read or even illegible due to faint ink, staining to leaves, and general damage.
Part of f. 358 torn away with loss of text in lower right corner of leaf.
Significant conservation and repair work undertaken on CUL MS Ee.5.22 in 2024.

layout.seg: Written in single-column format with no visible ruling. 41 lines to the leaf on a 'full' leaf, some leaves blank or sparsely written.

handNote.p: Written by several scribes, each using the anglicana form of cursiva antiquior.

decoNote.p: Minor initials have small decorative flourishes such as dots or decorative bars (or both) in the counterspaces.

additions.p: Quires numbered in pencil in Hindu-Arabic numerals in the lower outer corner of the first recto of each quire; the designation for Quire 18 has been omitted from this schema.
On folio 378v: a name 'Tailefere' in ink.
On folio 378v: a partially illegible note at the bottom of the leaf which includes the names 'John Goldwell' and 'Johannes Jacob'.

binding.p: 18th-century binding. Half bound in Russia leather with speckled light brown paper sides over paste or mill boards. No head or tail bands visible. No raised bands visible. Lower opening of spine torn - about 20mm of the bookblock exposed. Red leather title label tooled in gold 'READINGS ON STATUTES M.S.'. Three printed paper labels fixed to the spine with an adhesive, 'EE' '5' and '22' for the current shelfmark; all three stickers show signs of wear and damage.
Text in pencil on the left cover: 'Ee.5.22', 'Ee.v.22' and 'C'; the 'C' refers to a size-based classification and storage system used at Cambridge University Library.

Paper pastedowns pasted over the turn ins. The left pastedown contains the notes 'Ee.5.22' and 'C' in pencil for the present shelfmark and a size-based classification system used at Cambridge University Library.
One grey-brown paper flyleaf at each end of the volume (ff. i and ii), both blank.

accMat.p: One loose blank leaf of cream paper between the left pastedown and the first flyleaf (not photographed).

origin.origDate: Written in the second half of the 15th century, probably c. 1485. Date of production assigned on palaeographical grounds.
origin.p: Place of production assigned based on the script (Anglicana), the jurisdiction of much of the content of the volume (England), the occasional use of Middle English in the volume, and the presence of several English names in contemporary annotations and additions to the volume.

history.provenance: Baker and Ringrose describe some of the annotations on f. 50v as being in a hand 'resembling that of Francis Tate'. Francis Tate Tate, Francis, 1560-1616 was an English antiquary and politician as well as a Member of Parliament for Northampton and Shrewsbury.

provenance.p: John Moore (1646-1714), bishop of Ely Moore, John, 1646-1714 : no. 327 in Bernard, Catalogi librorum manuscriptorum Angliæ et Hiberniæ (c. 1697).

history.acquisition: Presented to the University Library in 1715 by George I George I, King of Great Britain, 1660-1727 : donation bookplate engraved by John Pine Pine, John, 1690-1756 in 1736 on f. 1v.

recordHist.source: This catalogue entry draws extensively on the description provided by John Baker and Jayne Ringrose, Catalogue of English Legal Manuscripts in Cambridge University Library (1996) (used here by kind permission of the Boydell Press). Readers are encouraged to consult this volume for further information about this item.

availability.p: Entry to read in the Library is permitted only on presentation of a valid reader's card. For information on eligibility and admissions procedures, see Joining the Library). For further information on the availability of the manuscript, please contact the Manuscripts Reading Room.

custodialHist.custEvent: In 2024, CUL MS Ee.5.22 received significant repair and conservation treatment from the CUL conservators in order to stabilise the volume. Every leaf in the volume was treated for damage and the irregular edges were rebuilt with conservation tissue to an approximately 'regular' shape with conservation tissue in order to prevent further damage to the irregular and fragile edges. The hinges, joints, covers and spine were all stabilised and repaired using appropriate methods.
